A new course at Harvard University this year makes all students sleep more in an attempt to fight the growing culture for learning “all night” with the help of caffeine.
The lecturer found that the students at University number one in the world often don't even think about it when it comes to the very foundations of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Kaysler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and the Women's Hospital, prepared the course he believes to be the first in his native state in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
"A girl finally came to me and said, "Why are they telling me now, in my last year?"
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which takes place for the first time this year, explains to the students the most important thing about how good sleep habits help academic and sports achievements, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barajra, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students suffer from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part there is a picture of a room in a dorm room where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, marathons and books to explain to them the effects of caffeine and light, how sports achievements influence the lack of sleep, as well as the importance of sleeping routine.
Another part of the participants tells how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Then a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that this will not immediately change students' behaviour.
But we believe that they have the right to know – just as you have the right to know the health effects of the choice to smoke," Professor Kaisler added.
The culture of pride from "Learning all night" still exists, he said, adding that modern technologies and the constantly increasing pressure on students mean that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring sufficient and quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students in the fight against stress, fatigue and anxiety, he says – even in order to avoid being overcharged, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in the hunger mode, which makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Kaisler prepare the course by taking one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
He says that his course “opened his eyes ” and inspired him to spread it throughout the campus.
It is hoped that the next step is for all graduate students to be asked to complete a similar training programme before joining the competitive institution.
