Solid allows consumers to choose where to store their data and which people have permission to access certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company Burners-Lei, it is a joke that the intention behind Inrupt is "world domination".
"We have to do it now," he said in terms of the initiative.
"This is a historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology that allows people to create their own “online storage of personal data” or Pod.
It contains lists, lists of tasks, calendars, music library and other personal and professional instruments.
It looks like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, which are available through every browser, and at the same time is all of them simultaneously.
The unique thing about the online storage of personal data is that the user determines who has access to what information.
The company calls it "the granting of personal data powers."
The idea for Inrupt, according to company CEO John Bruce, is to invest resources, processes and appropriate skills to help Solid become available to everyone.
Currently, the company consists of Burners-Ley, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers contracted work on the project, and a group of volunteer programmers.
As of this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralisation applications using tools available on Inrupt's website.
Burners-Lee said he and his team don't talk to Facebook and Google about whether to make a complete change, or not, when all their business models are completely renewed overnight.
"We don't want permission from them."
In a post in Medium on Saturday, Burners-Ley wrote that Inrupt's mission was to provide energy for trade and ecosystems to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid.
In 1994, Burners-Ley transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Technical Institute.
In recent months, Burners-Lee has had a strong impact on the network's neutrality debate.
Although Inrupt has started, Burners-Ley will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am extremely optimistic about this new era on the Internet," Burners-Lee added.
Bernard Van: In memory of a priest awarded with the cross Victoria during World War I
They are marked for 100 years in the hometown of the only English priest awarded with the cross Victoria for his participation in combat activities during World War I.
Lieutenant Colonel Bernard Van won the award on 29 September 1918 in the Bellenglise and Lehaukourt attacks.
Four days later, however, he was killed by a sniper without knowing that he was honored with Britain's highest military honors.
A memorial monument was found on Saturday by his two grandchildren, at a parade in Ruschden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandkids, Michael Van, said it was "extremely symbolic" for the monument to be discovered exactly 100 years after his grandfather's medal case.
According to London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Van led his battalion through the Canal de Saint-Quentin "in a very dense fog and under heavy fire from artillery and machine guns."
Later he attacked the fire line and with "incredible courage" led ahead before attacking an artillery cannon with one hand and killing three of the squad.
Lieutenant Colonel Van was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918 – only a month before the end of the war.
Michael Van, 72, said his grandfather's actions were “a thing I know I could never do, but it makes me feel humble. ”
He and his brother, Dr. James Van, set up a wreath after a parade led by Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Van said it is "a great honor for him to participate in the parade" and added "the virtue of the true hero is demonstrated through the support that will be given to many people."
