The four ships of the Baden-Wuertemberg class ordered by the Fleet in 2007 will replace the aged frigates of the Bremen class.
It is understandable that they will have a powerful weapon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-aircraft missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, e.g. reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – the newest frigates should be able to be used up to two years before returning to the ports of maturation.
However, continuous delays mean that the avant-garde warships – which are said to allow Germany to demonstrate power beyond the ocean – will already be old when they are put into service, notes Die Zeit.
The accident frigate F125 entered the headlines last year when the German fleet officially refused to release the vessel into service and returned it to Blohm & Voss Shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the fleet has returned a ship to a ship after delivery.
It is little known about the reasons for the return, but German media quoted a number of major "superficial and hardware defects" that make the military ship unusable if it is sent on a military mission.
Software disadvantages are particularly important, as the vessels of the Baden-Wuertemberg class will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors – only half of the crew of the older Fregates of the Bremen class.
In addition, it has proved that the ship is significantly overloaded, which reduces its efficiency and limits the possibility of the naval forces adding future superstructures.
The 7000-ton ‘Rheinland-Pfalz’ is considered to be twice as heavy as ships of a similar class used by Germans during World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project – including for crew training – also becomes a problem.
It is believed to have reached the stunning 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion dollars) from the initial 2.2 billion euros.
Problems with the latest frigates are becoming particularly important in light of recent warnings that Germany's military forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German Parliament's defence committee, admitted that the fleet is in fact "exhausted by ships capable of carrying out missions".
The official said the problem had become larger in time as the old ships were derived from operation but no new ones were provided.
He complained that no frigate of the Baden-Wuertemberg class could be included in the fleet.
The national reed follows the secret life of bats
A new survey carried out in an estate in the Scots Mountains aims to determine how bats use the landscape when they hunt.
Hopes are that discoveries will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation actions.
The study of scientists from the National Trieste of Scotland will follow the common bats, as well as the brown dart watery nightgowns at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations in the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using hand detectors.
The expert sound analysis of all records will determine the frequency of the bats' call sounds, as well as what types of bats they issue.
Then a map of habitats and a report will be drawn up to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Duar, a nature conservation adviser for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of work on habitat management, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and Britain generally decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction activities affecting their havens and leading to loss of habitats.
The risk to populations may be from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical treatment of construction materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats aren't blind.
However, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles on their flight trajectory.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of great importance and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Trieste has trained experts who conduct regular studies, inspections of shelters and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization even created the first in Scotland and the only special bat reserve at the Threave mansion in the Dumfries and Galaways, which is home to eight of the ten species of bats in Scotland.
The manager of the David Thompson mansion says it's the perfect territory for them.
"Here in Threave, we have a great field for bats," he noted.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and completed a suitable habitat.
But there are many more things about bats that are unknown, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us understand better what they need to thrive."
He stresses that it is important to check for bats before carrying out property maintenance activities, as it is possible for the accidental destruction of one asylum to kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as to destroy an entire local population.
The glues are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their havens.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee in the Trust to protect bats, encouraged society to help.
She said: “I still have much to learn about our bats and many of our animal species, because we just don’t know what happens to their populations. ”
