Nickel's gain is also important for the province, but it is concentrated mainly in Morovali, on the opposite shore of the Sulavesi.
Palu and Dongala have been hit several times by tsunamis in the last 100 years, according to data from the Indonesian disaster recovery agency.
In 1938, tsunamis killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of buildings in Dongala.
Tsunami hit the west end of Dongala in 1996 when nine people died.
Indonesia is located on the seismic “Tichokean ring of fire” and is regularly cut by earthquakes.
Here are some of the big earthquakes and waves of tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A strong earthquake on December 26th on the western coast of Indonesia’s province of Aceh in North Sumatra activates a wave of tsunamis that hit 14 countries and killed 226 000 people across the Indian Ocean’s coast, with more than half of them in Acech.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes struck the western coast of the Sumatra at the end of March and early April.
Hundreds died on Nias Island off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: Truss with a magnetod 6.8 cut off the most populated island in Indonesia, Java, triggering a tsunami that crashed in the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: Earthquake with a magnetod 7.6 struck near the city of Padang, the capital of the province of West Sumatra.
More than 1100 people died.
2010: Earthquake with a magnetod 7.5 cut one of the islands of Mentawai and activated a 10-foot tsunami wave that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake struck the regent Pidi Jaya in Aceh, causing destruction and panic, as people remembered the devastations of the deadly earthquakes and tsunamis in 2004.
This time, no tsunamis are activated, but more than 100 people were killed by collapsed buildings.
2018: Strong earthquakes cut down the island of Lombok in Indonesia, more than 500 people died, most of them on the north side of the island.
