Syria "ready" to return refugees, foreign minister said
Syria has announced that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is asking for assistance in the recovery of a country devastated by the war that has lasted more than seven years.
Addressing the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Muallem stressed that conditions in the country are improving.
"Today the situation in place is more stable and secure, thanks to the progress we have in fighting terrorism," he said.
The government continues to restore the areas devastationed by terrorists to restore them to their normal state.
Now there are all the conditions for voluntary return of refugees to the country, which they were forced to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and their diet.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Six more million people still living there need humanitarian help.
Al-Muallem said the Syrian regime would welcome any assistance in restoring the devastated state.
But he stressed that conditional support or assistance from countries that have funded the rebels would not be accepted.
