New for red inflow: Concentrations decrease in Pinelas, Manotti and Sarasota
The latest report by the Committee on Fish and Wildlife in Florida shows a general reduction in the concentrations of red inflows in sections of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Committee, there have been reports of growth gaps in the areas of Pinelas, Manotti, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts – this shows a decrease in concentrations.
The water sections with an excessive red inflow spread to approximately 130 miles along the coast, from the northern district of Pinelas to the southern district of Lee.
Seaweed sections can be seen 10 miles from the coast of Hillsborough, but they are less than last week.
The red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
In the past week, there have been reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal zone or slightly deeper in Pinelas County, low to high concentrations on the coast of the Hillsborough, high concentration assumptions in the Manotti County, high concentrations on the coast or within the Sarasota County, moderate concentration assumptions in Charlotte County, high concentration assumptions in the coast or deeper in the district of Lee, and low concentrations in the Collier County.
Reports of inflammation of the airways in Pinelas, Manoti, Sarasota, Lee and Collier districts continue.
No reports of respiratory tract inflammation in Northwestern Florida were received last week.
